    "reasoning": "Now I have all the calculations I need. Let me also calculate the contribution to growth:\n\nConnectivity contribution to consolidated growth:\n- Connectivity growth in $: $13,028 - $11,387 = $1,641M\n- Consolidated growth in $: $18,776 - $18,674 = $102M\n- So Connectivity growth ($1,641M) more than offsets the consolidated growth ($102M) because Space declined by $1,610M and AI grew by $71M\n\nLet me verify:\n- Space change: $2,476 - $4,086 = -$1,610M\n- Connectivity change: $13,028 - $11,387 = +$1,641M\n- AI change: $3,272 - $3,201 = +$71M\n- Total: -$1,610 + $1,641 + $71 = $102M \u2713\n\nSo Connectivity's growth ($1,641M) is more than 16x the consolidated growth ($102M). This means Connectivity is essentially carrying the entire consolidated growth, while Space is a major drag.\n\nLet me also calculate the contribution to growth percentages:\n- Connectivity contribution: $1,641 / $18,674 = 8.79% (i.e., if only Connectivity grew, consolidated would have grown 8.79%)\n- Space drag: -$1,610 / $18,674 = -8.62%\n- AI contribution: $71 / $18,674 = 0.38%\n- Net: 0.55%\n\nSo the consolidated growth of 0.55% is the net of:\n- Connectivity adding 8.79%\n- Space subtracting 8.62%\n- AI adding 0.38%\n\nThis shows that the consolidated momentum is highly concentrated in Connectivity, with Space being a major offsetting drag.\n\nLet me also calculate the share of consolidated revenue:\n- Q1 2026 Connectivity share: 69.39%\n- FY2025 Connectivity share: 60.98%\n- Increase in share: 8.41 percentage points\n\nThis further confirms the concentration of momentum in Connectivity.\n\nLet me also calculate the share of consolidated growth attributable to Connectivity:\n- Connectivity growth: $1,641M\n- Total positive growth (Connectivity + AI): $1,641 + $71 = $1,712M\n- Connectivity share of positive growth: $1,641 / $1,712 = 95.85%\n\nSo Connectivity accounts for ~96% of all positive growth across segments.\n\nNow let me prepare the final answer.",
